04820nam a22006975i 9780292737129DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011042851  a97802927371297 a10.7560/7292162doi  a(DE-B1597)588253  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aSB453.5b.G39 2012 4aSB453.5 ǂb G39 2012eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a635.9871 aGarrett, Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrganic Management for the Professional :bThe Natural Way for Landscape Architects and Contractors, Commercial Growers, Golf Course Managers, Park Administrators, Turf Managers, and Other Stewards of the Land /cHoward Garrett, Mike Amaranthus, John Ferguson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1: Introduction to Organics -- tChapter 2: Soil Building -- tChapter 3: Planting -- tChapter 4: Fertilizing -- tChapter 5: Pest and Disease Control -- tChapter 6: Compost -- tChapter 7: Mulch -- tChapter 8: Landscaping -- tChapter 9: Commercial Growing Operations and Recreational Properties -- tChapter 10: Organic Strategies and Global Climate Change -- tAppendix 1: Organic Treatment Formulas -- tAppendix 2: Sources for Organic Supplies -- tAppendix 3: Soil-Testing Resources -- tAppendix 4: Conversion Tables -- tInformation Resources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCan you manage the landscape of a golf course, city park, or corporate campus without synthetic fertilizers and toxic pesticides? Absolutely! Organic landscaping is not only possible on a large scale, but it also makes sense both economically and environmentally. It promotes healthy soils and plants, which require less water and sequester more carbon—a winning combination for both your bottom line and the planet’s fight against resource depletion and global warming. Organic programs on a commercial scale have enormous potential to make a difference in the quality of our environment, our use of fuels, and our climate. And as those who have already converted to organics have discovered, they also cost a lot less over the long term. Organic Management for the Professional is the first comprehensive guide to “going green” in large-scale landscaping. Nationally recognized organic gardening expert Howard Garrett, with associates John Ferguson and Mike Amaranthus, not only explains in detail how to manage projects with natural organic techniques, but also presents the material in clear, simple terms so that commercial and institutional property owners can understand what to ask of their landscape architects, contractors, growers, and maintenance people. They give detailed, proven instructions for the key components of organic landscaping—soil building, correct planting techniques, fertilizing, pest control, compost, and mulch. Then they show how to apply these organic methods in large-scale landscaping, commercial growing (orchards, tree farms, nurseries, and greenhouse operations), and recreational properties (golf courses, parks, and sports fields).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLandscape gardening. 0aOrganic gardening. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAmaranthus, Mike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFerguson, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72921640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292737129423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292737129/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA